🧠 3643. Flip Square Submatrix Vertically — Notes
🔹 Problem Essence

You are given:

A matrix grid
A square defined by:
top-left corner → (x, y)
size → k

👉 You need to flip this square vertically

🔹 What does “Flip Vertically” mean?

It means:

👉 Reverse the order of rows inside the square

So:

Row x         ↔ Row x + k - 1  
Row x + 1     ↔ Row x + k - 2  
...

Columns remain SAME ❗

🔹 Visualization
Before:
A
B
C
D
After vertical flip:
D
C
B
A
🔹 Core Idea 💡

We only need to:

Swap rows inside the square
But only within columns [y → y+k-1]
🔹 Algorithm
Step 1: Iterate half rows
for (i = 0 → k/2 - 1)

👉 Because each swap handles 2 rows

Step 2: Swap row elements column-wise
for (j = y → y+k-1)
    swap(grid[x+i][j], grid[x+k-1-i][j]);
🔹 Code Understanding (Line-by-Line)
for(int i = 0; i < k/2; i++)

👉 Traverse top half of square

for(int j = y; j < y+k; j++)

👉 Traverse all columns inside square

swap(grid[x+i][j], grid[x+k-1-i][j]);

👉 Swap:

top row → x+i
bottom row → x+k-1-i
🔹 Why k/2?

Because:

Each swap fixes 2 rows
Middle row (if k odd) stays same
🔹 Complexity
Time:
O(k * k) → only submatrix
Space:
O(1) → in-place
🔹 Edge Cases

✔️ k = 1 → no change
✔️ Square at boundary → still works
✔️ Odd k → middle row untouched

🔹 Pattern Recognition 🔥

This is classic:

✅ Matrix Subgrid + Symmetric Swap

Similar to:

reverse rows
rotate matrix
flip image
🔹 Mistakes to Avoid ❌
Swapping entire row instead of only [y → y+k-1]
Using full matrix columns

Wrong bottom index:

x+k-1-i  ✅
x+k-i    ❌
🔹 Quick Recall ⚡

👉 “Swap row i with row k-1-i inside the square columns”

🔹 Bonus Insight (Interview Level 🧠)

This is essentially:

Vertical reflection of a submatrix

If it was horizontal flip:

You’d swap columns instead
